               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290910-209-person1935">
                  EBENEZER 
                  BLAYNEY
               <interp inst="t18290910-209-person1935" type="surname" value="BLAYNEY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-209-person1935" type="given" value="EBENEZER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-209-person1935" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a <rs id="t18290910-209-viclabel1163" type="occupation">milkman</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290910-209-victim1934 t18290910-209-viclabel1163"></join>. On the 23rd of July I lost four milk-pails from my garden, in Queen-street, Hackney; I had seen them on the garden pails the night before - these are mine; I know nothing of the prisoner.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290910-209-person1936">
                  THOMAS 
                  WATERS
               <interp inst="t18290910-209-person1936" type="surname" value="WATERS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-209-person1936" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-209-person1936" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a Police-officer. On the 25th of July I went to the prisoner's house with a search-warrant; she is a kind of marine-store dealer, in Hackney-road; I found these pails up stairs; she said she bought them - I asked her for her book of the entry; she gave me one book, and I said, "It is not in this;" she said, "I have another, which my brother puts down things in, as I can't write myself:" I took her to the office, and soon after another book was brought, which had them entered; she said she had bought them some time, but she did not say of whom; she did not tell me the price, nor whether she bought them of a man, woman, or child.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I told the officer I bought them in an honourable way, gave 7s. for them, and exposed them at my door; one of the witnesses came and bought them, and gave me a deposit of a shilling, which induced me to take them in.</p>

               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290910-209-person1937">
                  JOHN 
                  BAILEY
               <interp inst="t18290910-209-person1937" type="surname" value="BAILEY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-209-person1937" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290910-209-person1937" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a chair-bottomer. I went into the prisoner's house to ask if she had any chairs to mend - I cannot tell the month, but it was on a Tuesday; I saw her give 7s. for these pails - she bought them of a tall man, in a drab coat; she gave him two half-crowns and two shillings - she called me to do some chairs, and offered me ninepence a piece to do them; I said I could not do them under a shilling.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18290910-209-verdict1164" type="verdictDescription">
